privatized through more gradual, democratic processes were able to make credible commitments to their citizens as well as to their multinational investors by including regulatory regimes with consumer protection mechanisms built in. Rhodes illustrates how consumers—previously unacknowledged actors in studies of social movements, market reforms, and democratizations in and beyond Latin America—are indispensable to understanding the political and social implications of these broad global trends.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aConsumer protectionzLatin AmericaxHistoryy20th century. 0aProtest movementszLatin AmericaxHistoryy20th century. 0aTelecommunicationxPrivatizationzLatin AmericaxHistoryy20th century. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Economic Policy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791482582423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791482582/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles